scala3: loading an extension needs an explicit `system`

On Scala 3, loading a 'classic' extension like `Tcp()` does not work:

```
[error] -- [E134] Type Error: /home/aengelen/dev/akka/akka-docs/src/test/scala/docs/stream/operators/flow/FromSinkAndSource.scala:54:4 
[error] 54 |    Tcp().bind("127.0.0.1", 9999).runForeach { incomingConnection =>
[error]    |    ^^^
[error]    |None of the overloaded alternatives of method apply in trait TcpImplicitExtensionIdApply with types
[error]    | (implicit system: akka.actor.ActorSystem): akka.stream.scaladsl.Tcp
[error]    | (system: akka.actor.ClassicActorSystemProvider): akka.stream.scaladsl.Tcp
[error]    |match arguments ()
```

Explicitly providing the ActorSystem, like `Tcp(system)`, does work.

Strangely, recreating the pattern in isolation:

```
trait ExtensionId[T] {
  def apply(i: Int): T = (new Tcp(i)).asInstanceOf[T]
  def apply(l: Long): T = (new Tcp(l.intValue)).asInstanceOf[T]
}
trait TcpImplicitExtensionIdApply extends ExtensionId[Tcp] {
  def apply()(implicit i: Int): Tcp = super.apply(i)
}
object Tcp extends ExtensionId[Tcp] with TcpImplicitExtensionIdApply {
}
class Tcp(i: Int) {
  def bind(): Unit = ()
}
object Main {
  implicit val i: Int = 42
  Tcp().bind()
}
```

... actually works fine.

I/O polling hangs when `computeWorkerThreadCount = 1`

First discovered this when debugging Native multithreading. It's also affecting CE 3.6.0-RC1 on the JVM, so it must be a WSTP / polling system integration bug.

```scala
//> using dep org.typelevel::cats-effect::3.6.0-RC1

import cats.effect.*
import java.nio.ByteBuffer
import java.nio.channels.Pipe
import java.nio.channels.SelectionKey._
import scala.concurrent.duration._

object Bug extends IOApp.Simple {
  override def computeWorkerThreadCount = 1 // changing to 2 fixes

  def run = mkPipe.use { pipe =>
    for {
      selector <- getSelector
      buf <- IO(ByteBuffer.allocate(4))
      _ <- IO(pipe.sink.write(ByteBuffer.wrap(Array(1, 2, 3)))).background
        .surround {
          selector.select(pipe.source, OP_READ) *> IO(pipe.source.read(buf))
        }
      _ <- IO(pipe.sink.write(ByteBuffer.wrap(Array(42)))).background.surround {
        selector.select(pipe.source, OP_READ) *> IO(pipe.source.read(buf))
      }
    } yield assert(buf.array().toList == List[Byte](1, 2, 3, 42))
  }.timeout(1.second)

  def getSelector: IO[Selector] =
    IO.pollers
      .map(_.collectFirst { case selector: Selector => selector })
      .map(_.get)

  def mkPipe: Resource[IO, Pipe] =
    Resource
      .eval(getSelector)
      .flatMap { selector =>
        Resource.make(IO(selector.provider.openPipe())) { pipe =>
          IO(pipe.sink().close()).guarantee(IO(pipe.source().close()))
        }
      }
      .evalTap { pipe =>
        IO {
          pipe.sink().configureBlocking(false)
          pipe.source().configureBlocking(false)
        }
      }
}
```
